# Mandatory documentation

Behavior changes, architectural changes, infrastructure changes, and operational workflows must include documentation updates. Documentation should remain aligned with the implemented system to preserve maintainability, onboarding quality, and organizational knowledge.

Apply this rule when:

- modifying system behavior
- updating architecture
- exposing new APIs
- modifying infrastructure
- changing operational workflows
- updating pipelines
- creating production pull requests

## Agent behavior

- In the same change (or linked follow-up the user approves): update READMEs, runbooks, ADRs, OpenAPI/contract docs, comments at module boundaries, or internal wikis—whatever this repo already uses for that topic.
- If no doc home exists: add the smallest appropriate doc in the established location (do not invent a large doc tree unless asked).
- In PR descriptions, list **which docs** were updated or explicitly state “no doc delta” with rationale only when truly no audience-facing or operator-facing change occurred.

## Example

```text
❌ BAD — New public API + deploy flag without changelog, README, or contract doc

✅ GOOD — Same PR updates API spec or README “Usage”, notes rollout/rollback in runbook or PR description, ADR only if architecture decision changed
```
